Comparing Motion Correction of Open-Source DWI Preprocessing Pipelines

Preamble

Im using the Masivar dataset for this project. The data Ive imported are developmental diffusion-weighted imaging (DWI) data. Though these data are longitudinal, Im only looking at the first session (and run) here. The raw diffusion data were preprocessed using two different pipelines, PreQual and QSI Prep. I then extracted multi- and single-shell diffusion metrics for the data processed using each pipeline. Motion metrics were calculated using the tools found here.

Data tidying

Now that all my data are imported, Im going to exclude subjects with high motion and plot a histogram showing age and sex. Ive excluded those with mean relative RMS > SD of 2.9 in keeping with Pines et al.(2020), and two participants were excluded for incomplete data.

qa_df <- qa_df %>% group_by(bval) %>%
  mutate(mean = mean(meanRELrms_b0.1),
         sd = sd(meanRELrms_b0.1)) %>%
  mutate(zscore = (meanRELrms_b0.1 - mean)/sd)
exclusions <- qa_df %>% filter(zscore > 2.9)
exclusions = c(unique(exclusions$participant_id),'cIVs066','cIVs101')
df_restricted <- qa_df %>% filter(!(participant_id %in% exclusions))

Lets take a look at a few things, just as a confidence check. I need a multi-shell measure of motion thats averaged across both shells, and Ill preemptively compute the log of this measure as well:

df_restricted <- df_restricted %>% group_by(participant_id) %>%
  mutate(ms_motion = mean(meanRELrms_b0.1)) %>%
  mutate(log_ms_motion = log(ms_motion))

Im actually also going to create a separate data frame for the multi-shell data to avoid accidentally duplicating all subjects in subsequent analyses.

df_restricted_ms <- df_restricted %>% filter(bval == 1000) %>%

Assessing the Impact of Motion

My next step was to use the approach in Pines, 2020 to see if there was residual motion in the preprocessed data that related to different diffusion metrics. First, Ill look at multi-shell data using the relative RMS displacement calculated from interspersed b0 values and averaged across the two shells and diffusion metrics calculated from a tensor fit to the multi-shell data.

Ill fit a separate model for each diffusion metric (FA, MD, RD, AD) and each pipeline and plot a visualization of the correlation. Ive just shown the code for QSI Prep MD; the rest is hidden but the plots are all displayed below.

# QSI MD
# First regress out age and sex
md_gam_nrms_qsi<-gam(global_md_qsi_ms~s(age,k=3)+sex,data=df_restricted_ms)
# Now look at correlation of residuals with motion 
df_restricted_ms$md_resid_nrms_qsi<-md_gam_nrms_qsi$residuals + 
  mean(df_restricted_ms$global_md_qsi_ms) 
cor_md_qsi <- cor.test(df_restricted_ms$log_ms_motion,df_restricted_ms$md_resid_nrms_qsi)
# And plot
qsi_md_plot <- ggplot(df_restricted_ms,aes(x=log_ms_motion,y=md_resid_nrms_qsi)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', colour=('#59b4c2'), fill = "#59b4c2", alpha = .3, lwd = 4) + 
  geom_point(alpha = .5, colour=('#59b4c2'), fill = "#59b4c2", size = 4) +
  ylab(element_blank()) + xlab(element_blank()) +
  ggtitle("QSI Prep") +
  my_theme +
  annotate("text", y=.00072, x=-.25, label= paste("r = ", round(cor_md_qsi$estimate,4)), 
           size = 8) +
  annotate("text", y=.00071, x=-.25, label= paste("p = ", round(cor_md_qsi$p.value,4)), 
           size = 8) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::number_format(accuracy = 0.00001), 
                     limits = c(.00070,.00080)) +
  my_theme

It seems the single-shell data tell the same story. Mike said something about how one of the pipelines may actually decorrelate age and motion. Which means PreQual gets rid of the association between age and motion, whereas QSI Prep may just get rid of motion itself. This could be why we still see motion effects in the PQ data but see stronger age effects thereafter. However, lets rerun my original GAMs and some nested version (???) to see what happens. And after, Ill run these GAMs but with single-shell motion metrics and subject as a random effect to see if this changes things.

Ill actually start with the GAMs I fit for my original poster for completeness. Here Im fitting two models to the data, with and without age, and seeing if adding age improves model fit by comparing with a chi-square anova.

anova(ad_gam_pq_nage, ad_gam_pq_age, test = "Chisq")

The results here are similar to before For QSI Prep, including age leads to marginally better model fits for md and ad, but with no significant effects of age.

For PreQual, including age leads to a marginally better model for MD but with no significant effect of age, but including age leads to a significantly better model fit for AD, with a significant effect of age and motion. Is it weird that including age increases the significance of the motion effect?
